    <h2 id="choosing-system">Choosing the Right System</h2>
    <p>
      System selection depends on oil viscosity, contamination type, and flow rate requirements. Light cutting oils with fine metal particles are well suited to the <a href="/centrifuges/dmpx-028/">DMPX-028</a>, while higher-volume operations or heavier quench oils may require the <a href="/centrifuges/dmpx-042/">DMPX-042</a>. Dolphin offers <a href="/industrial-centrifuge-sample-testing/">sample testing</a> to determine the optimal configuration for your specific fluid.
    </p>
    <p>
      Contact our engineering team at <a href="tel:+12485222573">(248) 522-2573</a> or <a href="/contact-for-alfa-laval-centrifuges/">request a quote</a> to discuss your oil-based fluid purification needs.
    </p>

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 pl-4 mb-4">
      <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer py-2">What contaminants does a centrifuge remove from cutting oil?</summary>
      <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">A disc stack centrifuge removes metal swarf, grinding dust, fine particles, scale, and moisture from cutting oils. Operating at 5,000–8,000 G, it captures particles below 1 micron that conventional cartridge filters miss — restoring cutting oil to near-virgin clarity and maintaining the surface finish quality required for precision machining.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 pl-4 mb-4">
      <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer py-2">How does centrifuge purification improve heat treatment quench oil performance?</summary>
      <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">Quench oil accumulates scale, carbon, and oxidation byproducts from repeated heating and quenching cycles. These contaminants reduce thermal conductivity and create hot spots that cause inconsistent part hardness. A centrifuge removes these contaminants continuously, restoring the uniform thermal performance needed for repeatable heat treatment results.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 pl-4 mb-4">
      <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer py-2">Can I use a centrifuge for neat (straight) cutting oil?</summary>
      <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">Yes. Neat cutting oils (non-emulsified straight oils) are ideal candidates for centrifuge purification. The centrifuge removes metal fines and moisture without disturbing the oil's chemistry. Dolphin Centrifuge systems process viscosities typical of most straight cutting oils without heating, though heated inlet lines may improve efficiency for very high-viscosity grades.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 pl-4 mb-4">
      <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer py-2">How often does a cutting oil centrifuge need maintenance?</summary>
      <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">Self-cleaning disc stack centrifuges (DMPX series) automatically eject sludge on a timed cycle and require minimal maintenance — typically a scheduled inspection every 6–12 months. Manual-clean models require more frequent attention depending on contamination load. Dolphin Centrifuge provides full service support and parts for every system we sell.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="border-l-4 border-gold/40 pl-4 mb-4">
      <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer py-2">What is the ROI for a cutting oil centrifuge installation?</summary>
      <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">Cutting oil centrifuge installations typically pay back in 6–18 months through reduced oil procurement costs, lower hazardous waste disposal fees, improved part quality, and reduced scrap. Customers commonly report oil replacement frequency dropping from monthly to every 3–5 years after installing centrifuge purification.</p>
    </details>

